#--: Introduction

This document is the architectural map of the zerolang typechecker.
It is intended to be read #_*"before" opening
#~"src/ztypecheck.py" (currently ~10,000 lines) -- after reading it,
a contributor should know which structures the typechecker
maintains, how its code is partitioned, and where a particular
feature lives.

The companion document #~"compiler.pdoc" covers #_*"semantics" --
what ownership means, how the multi-granularity lock-conflict rule
works, what demand-driven resolution guarantees. This document
covers #_*"structure": data layout, dispatch, code organisation.
The two documents are deliberately split so that semantic rules
have a single source of truth (compiler.pdoc / ownership.pdoc) and
this one stays a navigation aid that does not rot when rule wording
changes.

#b:"Audience." A new contributor who has already read
#~"spec.pdoc", #~"ownership.pdoc", and the Semantic-Analyser
section of #~"compiler.pdoc".


#--: Pipeline Position

The typechecker sits between the parser and the C emitter:

#code language=text: """
  zast.Program  (frozen post-parse)
      ↓   TypeChecker(program).check()
  ztyping.ZTyping  (mutable, holds all typecheck output)
      ↓
  CEmitter / zsqldump / zasthash
"""

The parser hands the typechecker a #~"zast.Program" -- an immutable
tree of #~"Node" subclasses, each with a monotonic #~"nodeid". The
typechecker does not mutate AST nodes; instead it writes its results
into a single mutable container, #~"ztyping.ZTyping", keyed by
#~"nodeid". After #~"check()" returns, the emitter and SQL dumper
read from both the #~"Program" (shape) and the #~"ZTyping" (types,
ownership, locks, monomorphisations) without further analysis.

#b:"Demand-driven, single pass." Resolution starts at #~"main" and
descends only into names that are actually referenced. Names that
are never reached are never typechecked. The same property gives
cycle detection for free -- a name that is encountered while it is
already on the resolution stack is reported as a circular
dependency. See #~"compiler.pdoc:Demand-Driven Resolution" for the
rationale.


#--: Core Data Structures

The typechecker is built around five core record types and one
mutable container. Reading this section first makes
#~"ztypecheck.py" considerably easier to follow, because nearly
every function in it produces, mutates, or consults one of these.


#---: ZType -- the unified type descriptor

#~"ZType" (in #~"src/ztypes.py") is the #_*"only" type
representation in the compiler. There is no separate "kind",
"shape", or "schema" object: every type -- record, class, variant,
union, protocol, facet, function, unit, numeric, native -- is a
#~"ZType" with a #~"typetype" discriminator (the #~"ZTypeType"
enum) and a set of optional fields.

Key fields:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"name": the simple name (e.g. #~"Point")]
  [#*: #~"typetype": the #~"ZTypeType" enum
    (#~"RECORD", #~"CLASS", #~"VARIANT", #~"UNION", #~"PROTOCOL",
    #~"FACET", #~"FUNCTION", #~"UNIT", numerics, ...)]
  [#*: #~"parent": the enclosing unit type, or #~"None"
    for top-level units]
  [#*: #~"children_id_map": per-name monotonic child id,
    minted lazily by #~"child_id_for(name)". The id is the
    authoritative key for children in #~"ZTyping.type_child" rows
    and for narrowing entries that need a numeric subject]
  [#*: #~"return_type", #~"return_ownership", #~"this_param_name":
    populated for function types]
  [#*: generic-state fields: #~"generic_params",
    #~"generic_defaults", #~"generic_origin",
    #~"numeric_generic_params", #~"is_tag_generic_origin"]
  [#*: #~"const_value": a literal value carried on a
    #~"ZType" used as either an as-block constant or a numeric
    generic-arg carrier (the #~"8" in #~"array<i64, 8>")]
  [#*: layout / memory metadata: #~"destructor_name",
    #~"is_heap_allocated", #~"needs_field_cleanup",
    #~"is_nullable_ptr", #~"is_box" (see
    #~"representation_of_types.pdoc")]
  [#*: #~"create_disabled", #~"meta_create":
    unified-call-dispatch metadata: bare-name calls route through
    #~"children[create]" unless disabled, with #~"meta_create"
    holding the raw allocator]
  [#*: #~"cname": the C identifier the emitter uses]
  [#*: #~"nodeid": monotonic id for SQL dumps]

A #~"ZType" carries identity-data only. #_*"Per-edge" metadata --
parameter ownership annotations, field defaults, lock/private
modifiers -- lives on #~"ZTyping.type_child" rows (the flat
children table), not on the parent #~"ZType".


#---: ZVariable -- per-binding ownership carrier

#~"ZVariable" (#~"src/ztypes.py") wraps a #~"ZType" with the
state that is per-variable rather than per-type. A #~"ZVariable"
is created only for #_*"named runtime bindings" -- function
parameters, locals introduced by assignment, #~"with"-bindings,
for-loop iterators, and synth temps -- and attached to
#~"ZEntry.var". Expression-level results live on #~"ZExprResult",
not here; type and function definitions also leave
#~"ZEntry.var = None".

#ul:
  [#*: #~"variableid": monotonic id]
  [#*: #~"ztype": the variable's resolved type]
  [#*: #~"ownership": #~"OWNED" or #~"BORROWED" (the
    2-state model described in #~"compiler.pdoc:Ownership and
    Lifetime")]
  [#*: #~"is_private_access": carried through #~".private"
    typedef projections]
  [#*: #~"borrow_origin": escape-analysis sentinel naming
    the function-local source this variable borrows from; #~"None"
    for parameters]
  [#*: #~"synth_origin": pass-name string for variables
    synthesised by a compiler pass (e.g. #~"\"anf\"" for hoisted
    call temps); #~"None" for user-source variables]

Keeping ownership off #~"ZType" lets the same type be bound in two
scopes with different ownership, which is the common case.


#---: ZEntry -- a scope binding

#~"ZEntry" (#~"src/ztypes.py") is the unit of scope state. Every
piece of information the scope chain needs to track about a name
lives on an #~"ZEntry":

#ul:
  [#*: #~"entry_id": monotonic id]
  [#*: #~"name", #~"ztype", #~"is_definition"]
  [#*: #~"var": optional #~"ZVariable" (absent for
    type/function definitions and lock-only overlays)]
  [#*: #~"lock": optional #~"ZLockInfo" carrying lock type,
    Holder, and the addressable path tuple #~"(root, f1, f2, ...)"]
  [#*: #~"narrowed_subtype", #~"narrowed_subtype_id",
    #~"excluded_subtypes", #~"excluded_subtype_ids": type
    narrowing for union / variant subjects in match arms, with
    id parallels for the future hot path]
  [#*: #~"original_ztype": the un-narrowed type, so the
    emitter can generate the C-level unwrap]
  [#*: #~"is_taken", #~"taken_at": consumed-binding state]

An entry is either a #_*"definition" (it introduces a name) or a
#_*"shadow / overlay" (it adjusts state for a name defined in an
outer scope). Definitions live in #~"BLOCK" scopes; shadows live
in #~"OVERLAY" or #~"CALL" scopes and disappear automatically when
their scope is popped. See #~"compiler.pdoc:Scope Environment" for
the three scope kinds.


#---: ZExprResult -- the result of checking an expression

Most expression-level helpers return #~"ZExprResult"
(#~"src/ztypes.py"), not a bare #~"ZType":

#ul:
  [#*: #~"ztype": the inferred type]
  [#*: #~"borrow_target": the addressable path tuple
    #~"(root, f1, ...)" that this expression borrows from; the
    enclosing #~"_check_assignment" / #~"_check_call_arguments"
    consumes it to install a borrow-scoped lock at the binding
    site]
  [#*: #~"private_access": propagated through
    #~".private" projections]

The #~"borrow_target" mechanism keeps borrow-lock installation
out of deep expression code: the leaf method that knows the source
path stamps it onto the #~"ZExprResult", and the eventual binding
site installs the lock. The flow is described under
#~"ownership.pdoc:Borrow propagation".


#---: ZTyping -- the typecheck-output container

#~"ZTyping" (#~"src/ztyping.py") is the single mutable container
holding everything the typechecker computes. It is intentionally
ECS-shaped: instead of decorating parsed AST nodes with
#~"init=False" columns, the typechecker writes into a set of
#~"Dict[nodeid, value]" component tables.

Aggregate state:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"parsed": back-reference to the immutable
    #~"zast.Program"]
  [#*: #~"errors", #~"is_error": error accumulator]
  [#*: #~"mono_types", #~"mono_functions": monomorphised
    generic instantiations, each paired with its origin AST
    definition]
  [#*: #~"func_aliases", #~"cloned_methods", #~"resolved":
    monomorphisation deduplication caches]
  [#*: #~"unit_types_by_id": Unit-AST nodeid → resolved unit
    ZType]
  [#*: #~"symbol_table": the live #~"ZSymbolTable" (typed via
    #~"ZSymbolTableProto" to keep #~"ztyping" decoupled from
    #~"zenv")]

Component tables (each keyed by parsed-node #~"nodeid"):

#ul:
  [#*: #~"node_type", #~"node_const_value": per-Node type
    and compile-time constant]
  [#*: #~"call_kind", #~"call_callable_type_name",
    #~"expr_call_kind": call classification and control-kind
    routing]
  [#*: #~"do_has_break", #~"case_subject_taken",
    #~"for_iter_bindings": per-construct flags]
  [#*: #~"if_taken_vars", #~"case_taken_vars": post-branch
    ownership-cleanup lists]
  [#*: #~"atom_narrowed_subtype", #~"atom_original_ztype",
    #~"atom_child_id": per-AtomId narrowing stamps]
  [#*: #~"dp_parent_tagged_type", #~"dp_child_id": per-
    DottedPath parent-type and child-id stamps]
  [#*: #~"with_ownership", #~"with_alias_of",
    #~"assign_alias_of": per-binding alias/ownership stamps]
  [#*: #~"projected_args": per-NamedOperation protocol-projection
    stamps]
  [#*: #~"type_child", #~"type_generic_arg": flat
    children / generic-args tables, replacing the prior
    per-ZType dict columns]

The SQL dumper writes one row per dict, so every component table
has a direct SQL representation.


#---: ZSymbolTable and ZScope

#~"ZSymbolTable" (#~"src/zenv.py") is the scope stack the
typechecker uses for #_*"all" variable state -- type, ownership,
lock state, narrowing, taken state. There is no separate flow-
typing structure: state changes are recorded as new entries in
overlay scopes; scope pop is the only thing that undoes them.

#ul:
  [#*: #~"ZScope": holds #~"entries: List[ZEntry]" (linear
    scan rather than a dict; typical scope has fewer than ten
    entries), a #~"kind" (#~"BLOCK", #~"CALL", or #~"OVERLAY"),
    a #~"name", an #~"unreachable" flag, and a monotonic
    #~"scope_id"]
  [#*: #~"ZSymbolTable": stack of #~"ZScope" frames plus
    #~"_history" (popped scopes, retained for SQL dump) and
    #~"scope_log" (append-only log of push/pop events with
    parent ids and sequence numbers)]

Three scope kinds (full description in
#~"compiler.pdoc:Scope Environment"):

#ul:
  [#*: #~"BLOCK" -- language constructs (function, do, for, if,
    with, match arm). Can contain definitions.]
  [#*: #~"CALL" -- pushed before processing call arguments, popped
    after the call. Locks installed here vanish when the call
    returns.]
  [#*: #~"OVERLAY" -- shadow records for a variable defined in an
    outer scope (new lock, narrowing, taken state).]

Lock state is keyed on a path tuple #~"(root, f1, ..., fn)" stored
on #~"ZLockInfo". #~"ZEntry.name" always equals #~"path[0]" so the
linear scan stays cheap; the full tuple is consulted only by the
prefix-overlap rule. Key APIs (all on #~"ZSymbolTable"):

#ul:
  [#*: #~"lookup", #~"lookup_var", #~"lookup_var_by_id",
    #~"lookup_entry" -- name → type / variable / entry resolution]
  [#*: #~"try_lock" -- attempt to install a lock; returns
    #~"ZLockInfo" or a conflict description. Multi-granularity
    rule is in #~"_lock_acquire_conflict"]
  [#*: #~"find_exclusive_lock", #~"is_path_locked" -- access-
    site enforcement (used by lock-escape checks)]
  [#*: #~"narrow", #~"exclude" -- install a narrowing or
    exclusion overlay entry on the current scope]

The lock conflict logic lives in #~"zenv.py", not in
#~"ztypecheck.py". The typechecker only chooses #_*"when" to
install a lock; the rule for whether it conflicts is owned by
the scope module.


#--: Code Map of #~"ztypecheck.py"

The file is long, but it organises top-to-bottom roughly as
follows. Functions are listed by name (no line numbers -- they
rot fast; #~"grep -n" finds them quickly). Use this map to scroll
into the right region; read prose below for the semantics.

#table:
  [#tr: [#th: Band] [#th: Key functions]]
  [#tr: [#td: TypeChecker init]
        [#td: #~"__init__" -- resolving stack, unit cache,
              #~"_definition_resolvers" dispatch table, call-id
              stack, fresh-namer for hoisting, MonoState,
              TemplateIds, FunctionContext]]
  [#tr: [#td: Entry point]
        [#td: #~"check" -- starts at #~"main", drives demand-
              driven resolution and body checking, returns the
              accumulated error list]]
  [#tr: [#td: Unit-level name resolution]
        [#td: #~"_resolve_unit_name", #~"_type_of_definition"
              (dispatches over #~"NodeType" via the
              #~"_definition_resolvers" dict)]]
  [#tr: [#td: Type-definition resolvers]
        [#td: #~"_resolve_function_type",
              #~"_resolve_record_type", #~"_resolve_class_type",
              #~"_resolve_union_type",
              #~"_resolve_variant_type",
              #~"_resolve_protocol_type",
              #~"_resolve_facet_type",
              #~"_resolve_inline_unit_type", #~"_resolve_tag",
              #~"_resolve_data_type"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Name and typeref resolution]
        [#td: #~"_resolve_name", #~"_resolve_typeref",
              #~"_resolve_typeref_call",
              #~"_resolve_type_keyword",
              #~"_resolve_this_keyword",
              #~"_resolve_dp_parent_type",
              #~"_resolve_dotted_path"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Monomorphisation]
        [#td: #~"_monomorphize", #~"_mono_arg_key",
              #~"_monomorphize_function",
              #~"_check_mono_constraints"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Function body]
        [#td: #~"_check_function_body",
              #~"_check_function_body_inner"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Statements]
        [#td: #~"_check_statement",
              #~"_check_statement_inner",
              #~"_check_statement_line",
              #~"_check_statement_line_inner",
              #~"_check_assignment",
              #~"_check_reassignment", #~"_check_swap"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Expressions]
        [#td: #~"_check_expression", #~"_check_operation",
              #~"_check_path", #~"_check_atomid",
              #~"_check_string_interpolation"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Dotted paths]
        [#td: #~"_check_dotted_path" (auto-call coercion gate
              via #~"coerce_method_to_return"),
              #~"_check_dotted_path_inner",
              #~"_check_dp_take", #~"_check_dp_release",
              #~"_check_dp_borrow", #~"_check_dp_lock",
              #~"_check_dp_private"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Calls]
        [#td: #~"_check_call", #~"_check_call_inner",
              #~"_check_call_arguments",
              #~"_check_missing_call_args",
              #~"_check_missing_create_args",
              #~"_apply_take_to_arg", #~"_lock_arg",
              #~"_lock_receiver", #~"_install_borrow_locks",
              #~"_check_aggregate_lock_escape",
              #~"_check_protocol_create",
              #~"_check_protocol_borrow",
              #~"_check_typedef_create",
              #~"_check_typedef_borrow"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Special call forms]
        [#td: #~"_check_return_call" (unified
              #~"children[create]" dispatch),
              #~"_check_str_convert_call", #~"_check_binop"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Control flow]
        [#td: #~"_check_if", #~"_check_exhaustive_if",
              #~"_check_for", #~"_check_with",
              #~"_check_case" (match arm checking, including
              branch narrowing and post-match exclusion),
              #~"_check_box_construction"]]


#--: Dispatch Mechanism

Per the project convention (#~"CLAUDE.md"), the typechecker uses
field-based dispatch on the #~"NodeType" enum rather than
#~"isinstance". The pattern appears in two forms:

#ul:
  [#*: #b:"Dict-of-bound-methods built at init time" -- e.g.
    #~"_definition_resolvers" (NodeType → resolver method).
    Used where the set of cases is closed and known up front
    (type-definition resolvers, statement-line kinds). Lookup is
    O(1) and avoids #~"getattr"-by-name.]
  [#*: #b:"Inline switch on" #~"node.nodetype" -- used inside
    #~"_check_expression", #~"_check_path", and a few similar
    high-fan-out helpers where a flat #~"if / elif" chain reads
    more clearly than a table.]

#~"cast()" is used after the discriminator check to narrow the
node type for the static type checker (#~"ty"); see
#~"src/zast.py".


#--: Resolution Stack and Cycle Detection

#~"TypeChecker._resolving" is the list-shaped resolution stack:
each entry is a #~"(qualified_name, ZType)" tuple. The flow is:

#ol:
  [#*: #~"_resolve_unit_name(unit, name)" checks
    #~"self._resolved" -- a cache of fully-resolved unit-level
    names. Hit: return immediately.]
  [#*: Cache miss: push #~"(qualified, placeholder_ztype)" onto
    #~"_resolving", dispatch to the appropriate
    #~"_resolve_*_type" via #~"_definition_resolvers".]
  [#*: If a nested resolution re-enters the same qualified name,
    the resolver finds it on the stack and reports a
    cycle error.]
  [#*: On success, the resolver pops the stack frame and writes
    the final #~"ZType" into #~"_resolved".]

The #~"type" keyword (in receiver position) resolves to the type
at the bottom of the resolving stack, so a method body can refer
to its own enclosing type without naming it. #~"this" works
similarly via #~"_resolve_this_keyword".


#--: Cross-Cutting Concerns

Each subsection below points at #_*"where" a concern lives in the
typechecker. For #_*"why" it works that way, follow the links to
the semantic documents.


#---: Ownership enforcement

The 2-state ownership model (see #~"compiler.pdoc:Ownership and
Lifetime") is enforced at the assignment and call sites:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"_check_assignment" -- definition site. Records the
    new variable's ownership in a fresh #~"ZVariable", consumes
    any #~"ZExprResult.borrow_target" by installing a borrow
    lock.]
  [#*: #~"_check_reassignment" -- enforces that the LHS variable
    is currently #~"OWNED" and that the RHS provides the
    appropriate ownership; resets narrowing and re-runs lock
    escape checks.]
  [#*: #~"_check_swap" -- symmetric ownership preservation.]
  [#*: #~"_apply_take_to_arg" -- argument-site #~".take";
    transfers ownership from the caller's binding into the
    callee's parameter.]

Parameters default to #~".borrow"; #~".take" and #~".lock" are
the opt-in transfers. The annotations live on
#~"ZTyping.type_child.param_ownership", not on the parameter
#~"ZType".


#---: Lock checking

The typechecker chooses #_*"when" to install a lock; #~"zenv.py"
owns the conflict rule (#~"_lock_acquire_conflict") and the
prefix-overlap path test (#~"_paths_overlap"). Two scopes of
locks, both described in #~"compiler.pdoc:Lock Checking":

#ul:
  [#*: #b:"Call-scoped" -- installed by #~"_lock_receiver" /
    #~"_lock_arg" inside a #~"CALL" scope that wraps argument
    processing. The leaf is #~"EXCLUSIVE"; every intermediate
    prefix is #~"SHARED".]
  [#*: #b:"Borrow-scoped" -- installed by
    #~"_install_borrow_locks" when a binding takes a borrow into
    a #~"BLOCK" scope (#~".borrow", #~".lock", #~".stringview",
    #~"with", or a #~".lock"-param transfer). Persists for the
    lifetime of the binding's scope; released by scope pop or
    explicit #~".release".]

#~"_check_aggregate_lock_escape" runs at storage sites (field
writes) and at return sites; it consults #~"is_path_locked" on
the scope chain to reject a write/return that would let a locked
value escape its scope.

Self-overlap during a single call (e.g.
#~"f.method bv: f.byteview") is permitted via the call-identity
stack (#~"_call_id_stack" + #~"ZLockHolder" tagging): #~"try_lock"
skips the conflict check when the existing Holder matches the
current call's identity.


#---: Borrow correctness for parameters

Deep methods that take a borrow into a return value record the
source path on #~"_pending_borrow_lock", which
#~"_check_expression" captures into #~"ZExprResult.borrow_target"
and clears so it cannot leak across statements. The binding site
(#~"_check_assignment" or #~"_check_call_arguments") then
installs the borrow lock against the actual destination scope.
The dedicated deep helpers live under #~"_check_dp_*"
(#~"_check_dp_borrow", #~"_check_dp_lock",
#~"_check_dp_release", #~"_check_dp_private",
#~"_check_dp_take").


#---: Monomorphisation

Generic types and functions are monomorphised by deep-cloning
the original AST subtree, binding the generic parameters to
concrete types, and re-running the standard resolvers on the
clone.

#ul:
  [#*: #~"_monomorphize" -- entry for generic type
    instantiation. Builds a deduplication key via
    #~"_mono_arg_key" (a tuple over arg #~"(name, const_value)"
    pairs so numeric generics also dedupe), reuses an existing
    instantiation if present, otherwise clones and registers
    into #~"ZTyping.mono_types".]
  [#*: #~"_monomorphize_function" -- per-function variant.
    Clones the function AST, binds generic params, typechecks
    the clone with the mono context in scope.]
  [#*: #~"_check_mono_constraints" -- enforces generic
    constraints on a candidate argument type.]

Cloned nodes carry #~"synth_origin" (the pass-name string) so the
SQL dump and asthash can attribute them to monomorphisation
rather than to the user. The synthesis toolkit
(#~"src/zsynth.py") is documented in
#~"compiler.pdoc:Synthesis Toolkit"; the same toolkit is used by
per-call argument hoisting.

#~"is native" methods (the compiler-provided collection methods
on #~"array", #~"List", #~"Map", #~"str", etc.) are #_*"not"
special-cased -- they are cloned alongside user methods. The
only requirement is that their declaration in
#~"lib/system/system.z" or #~"lib/system/collections.z" carries
the #~"is native" form. Resolution flows through the standard
child-lookup path.


#---: Type narrowing

Narrowing for #~"union" and #~"variant" subjects in match arms
is implemented via overlay entries. When a match arm narrows
subject #~"s" to subtype #~"ok", an overlay #~"ZEntry" with
#~"narrowed_subtype: \"ok\"" is pushed onto the arm's scope.
Inside the arm, name lookup for #~"s" finds this entry first and
returns the narrowed type. The arm scope is popped at end of
arm; narrowing resets automatically.

Post-match #_*"exclusion" is the dual: arms that diverge
(return, break, panic) contribute their handled subtypes to an
#~"excluded_subtypes" entry placed on the parent scope after the
match. Subsequent code that re-accesses #~"s" as an excluded
subtype is rejected.

Assignment-based narrowing (e.g. #~"x: Result.ok 42") places a
narrowing entry in the current scope at definition time;
reassignment resets it.

Both narrowing and exclusion carry id parallels
(#~"narrowed_subtype_id", #~"excluded_subtype_ids") minted via
#~"ZType.child_id_for". String fields remain authoritative; the
ids are the hot-path key prepared for future migration to the
SQL-backed representation.


#---: Auto-call coercion

A no-user-arg method dotted path read in value position
(#~"v: s.stringview", #~"p1.distance" inside a string
interpolation) is auto-called to its return type. The coercion
lives entirely in #~"_check_dotted_path" and is gated by a
#~"coerce_method_to_return" parameter. #~"_check_call" flips the
flag off when resolving its own callable, so explicit calls
(#~"obj.method named: arg") see the function type and dispatch
normally instead of constructing the return type. Path
resolution itself (#~"_resolve_dotted_path") is context-free: it
always returns the FUNCTION type for a method path. Behaviour is
identical for #~"is native" and user-defined methods.


#---: Unified call dispatch

A type used in callable position is rewritten through the
unified-dispatch route. The bare-name construction call
#~"Point x: 1 y: 2" resolves the callee to the #~"Point"
#~"ZType", then looks up #~"children[create]" on that type to
get the actual constructor. The mechanics live in
#~"_check_return_call" and friends; #~"meta.create" on the
parent #~"ZType" carries the compiler-generated raw allocator
when one is needed. #~"create: null" in the type's #~"as" block
disables bare-name construction (the case for #~"union" and
#~"variant" where subtype selection is required).


#--: Error Reporting

Type errors are #~"zast.Error" value objects, appended to
#~"self.errors" via the #~"_error()" helper. Errors are never
raised as exceptions; the typechecker tries to continue
collecting errors past the first failure where the AST permits.
Error codes (the #~"ERR" enum in #~"src/zast.py") are grouped:

#ul:
  [#*: E0001-E0099 -- parser / syntax (raised earlier in the
    pipeline)]
  [#*: E0100-E0199 -- type resolution]
  [#*: E0200-E0299 -- ownership]
  [#*: E0300-E0399 -- call / argument]
  [#*: E0400-E0499 -- generic / monomorphisation]

The diagnostic location is taken from the offending AST node's
#~"loc" / #~"Token". After #~"check()" returns, the caller
inspects #~"typing.errors" (or the return value of #~"check()")
to decide whether to proceed to emission.


#--: What Lives Elsewhere

Module boundaries the typechecker relies on:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"src/ztypes.py" -- #~"ZType", #~"ZVariable",
    #~"ZEntry", #~"ZExprResult", #~"ZLockInfo", #~"ZLockHolder",
    plus the #~"ZTypeType" / #~"ZOwnership" /
    #~"ZParamOwnership" / #~"ZLockState" / #~"ZScopeKind" /
    #~"ZSubType" / #~"ZControlKind" / #~"ZBuiltinFunc" /
    #~"ZLockHolderKind" enums]
  [#*: #~"src/ztyping.py" -- the #~"ZTyping" container,
    #~"ZTypeChild" / #~"ZTypeGenericArg" flat-table rows]
  [#*: #~"src/zenv.py" -- #~"ZSymbolTable", #~"ZScope",
    #~"ZScopeLogRow", the lock-conflict logic
    (#~"_lock_acquire_conflict", #~"_paths_overlap"), narrowing
    / exclusion installers]
  [#*: #~"src/ztypeutil.py" -- collection-type predicates
    (#~"is_array_type", #~"is_list_type", #~"list_element_type",
    ...) shared between typechecker and emitter]
  [#*: #~"src/zsynth.py" -- node synthesis toolkit
    (#~"FreshNamer", #~"make_atom_id", #~"make_assignment",
    #~"register_synth_var") used by per-call hoisting and
    auto-generated equality]
  [#*: #~"src/zsymtab_proto.py" -- the duck-typed
    #~"ZSymbolTableProto" that breaks the
    #~"zast" ↔ #~"zenv" import cycle]
  [#*: #~"src/zasthash.py" -- structural hashing used by the
    monomorphisation dedup key]


#--: Reading Order

When opening the typechecker for the first time, read in this
order:

#ol:
  [#*: #~"src/ztypes.py" -- the dataclass definitions in this
    file are the vocabulary for everything else.]
  [#*: #~"src/ztyping.py" -- the #~"ZTyping" container makes the
    component-table architecture concrete.]
  [#*: #~"src/zenv.py" -- the scope stack and the lock-conflict
    rule. The semantics of "what makes two locks conflict" lives
    here, not in the typechecker.]
  [#*: #~"src/ztypecheck.py" -- enter via the Code Map above.
    A good first dive is #~"check()" → #~"_resolve_unit_name" →
    #~"_resolve_function_type" → #~"_check_function_body" →
    #~"_check_statement" → #~"_check_expression" →
    #~"_check_call". That path touches almost every cross-
    cutting concern in turn.]
  [#*: #~"src/zsynth.py" -- read once you encounter a hoisted
    temp in a SQL dump or test snapshot.]


#--: Related Documents

#ul:
  [#*: #~"compiler.pdoc" -- the pipeline overview and the
    semantic descriptions of demand-driven resolution,
    monomorphisation, ownership, scope environment, lock
    checking, type narrowing, and the synthesis toolkit. This
    document is the structural companion to that one.]
  [#*: #~"ownership.pdoc" -- the full specification of
    ownership states, parameter annotations
    (#~".take" / #~".borrow" / #~".lock"), and per-call atomic
    processing.]
  [#*: #~"representation_of_types.pdoc" -- type layout
    (#~"destructor_name", #~"is_heap_allocated",
    #~"needs_field_cleanup", #~"is_box") and the stack-vs-heap
    strategy.]

#b:"Anti-duplication note." Semantic rules live in
#~"compiler.pdoc" and #~"ownership.pdoc"; type layout lives in
#~"representation_of_types.pdoc". This document is the map. If a
rule's wording needs to change, change it there, not here.
